Establising results statistically¶

A p-value or probability value is the measure of statistical model wherein null hypothesis is accepted or rejected based on the measure of p-value.

In [44]:
charges_of_smoker = np.array(df[df['smoker']=='yes'].charges)
charges_of_non_smoker = np.array(df[df['smoker']=='no'].charges)

t, p_value  = stats.ttest_ind(charges_of_smoker,charges_of_non_smoker, axis = 0)

if p_value < 0.05:  # Setting our significance level at 5%
    print(f'Alternate Hypothesis: Difference in charges ({p_value}) < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'Null Hypothesis: No difference in charges ({p_value}) > 0.05')

Alternate Hypothesis: Difference in charges (8.271435842177219e-283) < 0.05

Establising results statistically¶

A p-value or probability value is the measure of statistical model wherein null hypothesis is accepted or rejected based on the measure of p-value.

In [35]:
bmi_of_female = np.array(df[df['sex']=='female'].bmi)
bmi_of_male = np.array(df[df['sex']=='male'].bmi)

t, p_value  = stats.ttest_ind(bmi_of_female,bmi_of_male, axis = 0)

if p_value < 0.05:  # Setting our significance level at 5%
    print(f'Alternate Hypothesis: Difference in bmi with respect to sex({p_value}) < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'Null Hypothesis: No difference in bmi with respect to sex ({p_value}) > 0.05')

Null Hypothesis: No difference in bmi with respect to sex (0.08997637178984932) > 0.05

crosstab = pd.crosstab(df['sex'],df['smoker'])  # Contingency table of sex and smoker attributes

chi, p_value, dof, expected =  stats.chi2_contingency(crosstab)

if p_value < 0.05:  # Setting our significance level at 5%
    print(f'Gender has an effect as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'Gender has no effect as the p_value ({p_value.round(3)}) > 0.05')
